<font color="#FF0000">VISITING THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec 23 11:27:14 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I've been to the Wall twice now, once in the 80's by myself and again in '92 with my wife.<br><br>
I haven't tried to look up any names, in fact I haven't even tried to look at individual names as there is a part of me that doesn't really want to find the name of a friend I thought to be safe and home.  I can only look from a distance.<br><br>
I cannot stay long, maybe 10 or 15 minutes is the limit for me.  It isn't the wall so much, it's the people.  The parents and children, the friends and lovers.  What could I say to them if they talked to me?  What could I tell them that would help?<br><br>
And then, there are the vets.  The ones who can't give up wearing thier field jackets, the ones who come in costume to be recognized, to be associated with the names as though that will heal them.  I look at thier faces but I don't remember them, the faces I remember are young/old and these are just old like those you see hunched over the bar at the local VFW.<br><br>
A part of me expected each time to suddenly find myself face to face with Tony or Chuck, with Wagner or Mahon, with Eichelberger or someone who's name has faded with the years, but who's face is still etched on my memory.  Or maybe even Barbara who's &quot;Dear John&quot; letter I still keep.  But this didn't happen, perhaps for the better.  But I still can't look at the names, I wouldn't want to find them that way.<br><br>
It isn't likely that I'll go again.  The years are building up and its a long way from California to the Wall, it was closer for those who's names are there.<br>
   
